[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We must partition a given integer N into positive summands whose total sum is exactly N, so that the LCM of the summands is as large as possible.  
   - Secondary requirement: among all optimal‐LCM partitions, output the lexicographically smallest (when each partition is sorted in nondecreasing order).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - Key observation: an integer's contribution to the LCM is via prime powers.  If you want the LCM to contain pᵏ, you can either pick one number divisible by pᵏ, or combine separate prime powers in one composite—yet picking them separately (pᵏ and qˡ) always costs ≤ pᵏ·qˡ, so it never pays to merge distinct prime powers into one composite.  
   - Thus we reduce to a multiple‐choice (grouped) 0/1 knapsack: for each prime p≤N, choose at most one exponent k (1 ≤ k ≤ ⌊logₚ N⌋), which contributes weight = pᵏ (the “cost” toward the sum) and value = log(pᵏ).  We have total capacity = N.  
   - After choosing prime powers whose total weight ≤ N, any leftover sum is filled with 1’s (they don’t change the LCM).  To be lexicographically smallest, we use *all* leftover as 1’s (more leading 1’s is lexicographically smaller) and we keep our chosen prime‐powers in ascending order of pᵏ.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Let π(N)≈669 be the number of primes ≤5000.  Each prime p has O(logₚN) power‐options (summed over all p this is ≲2000).  
   - We do a standard DP over capacity N (up to 5000) and for each group (prime) we scan j=0…N and options pᵏ, so ≲(2000⋅5000)≈10^7 transitions.  
   - Each transition carries a small vector copy (average length ~5–10).  This runs in well under 1s in optimized C++ for N≤5000.  
   - Space: O(N) states, each storing a double + small vector, O(N⋅avg_len)≈ O(5000⋅10)=50k ints.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - N=1 ⇒ no prime powers can be chosen, so we output a single "1".  
   - Floating‐point comparisons: we compare sums of logs and use a small epsilon.  
   - Lex‐tie breaking: among equal‐value states we prefer the one with **more** leftover for 1’s (i.e. smaller total cost) to get more leading 1’s; if still tied, we compare the chosen prime‐powers lexicographically.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Solution to "LCM Partition" by grouped 0/1 knapsack over prime‐powers.
  We maximize sum of logs of chosen prime‐powers (equivalently maximizing LCM),
  then fill leftover with 1's for exact sum N, yielding lexicographically minimal.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

static const double NEG_INF = -1e300;
static const double EPS = 1e-9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N;
    cin >> N;

    // 1) Sieve primes up to N
    vector<bool> is_composite(N+1, false);
    vector<int> primes;
    for(int i = 2; i <= N; i++){
        if(!is_composite[i]){
            primes.push_back(i);
            if((long long)i * i <= N)
                for(int j = i*i; j <= N; j += i)
                    is_composite[j] = true;
        }
    }

    // 2) For each prime, precompute its powers ≤ N
    //    and their log-values.
    int P = primes.size();
    vector<vector<pair<int,double>>> options(P);
    for(int idx = 0; idx < P; idx++){
        int p = primes[idx];
        long long w = p;
        while(w <= N){
            options[idx].push_back({int(w), log((double)w)});
            w *= p;
        }
    }

    // 3) DP array: dp[c] = best state for total cost c
    struct State {
        double val;          // sum of logs = log(LCM)
        vector<int> sel;     // chosen prime-powers (strictly increasing)
    };

    vector<State> dp(N+1);
    // init
    for(int c = 1; c <= N; c++){
        dp[c].val = NEG_INF;
    }
    dp[0].val = 0.0;  // no prime-powers, LCM=1 => log=0

    // 4) Grouped knapsack over primes
    for(int idx = 0; idx < P; idx++){
        auto nxt = dp;  // copy current dp to nxt
        for(int c = 0; c <= N; c++){
            if(dp[c].val <= NEG_INF/2) continue;
            // try pick one power of prime primes[idx]
            for(auto &opt: options[idx]){
                int w = opt.first;
                double lg = opt.second;
                int nc = c + w;
                if(nc > N) break;
                double nv = dp[c].val + lg;
                auto &st = nxt[nc];
                bool better = false;
                if(nv > st.val + EPS){
                    better = true;
                } else if (fabs(nv - st.val) <= EPS) {
                    // tie on LCM; prefer lex-smaller -> but first we want
                    // more leftover= smaller nc  => more leading 1's
                    // since we store by exact cost nc, we'll resolve after full DP.
                    // Here we only compare the sel vectors for the same nc.
                    vector<int> cand = dp[c].sel;
                    cand.push_back(w);
                    if(cand < st.sel) better = true;
                }
                if(better){
                    // accept new state
                    st.val = nv;
                    st.sel = dp[c].sel;
                    st.sel.push_back(w);
                }
            }
        }
        dp.swap(nxt);
    }

    // 5) Extract best among dp[0..N]:
    //    maximize (val, leftover = N-c), tie-break val, leftover
    //    if STILL tie, tie-break sel lex.
    double bestVal = NEG_INF;
    int bestCost = 0;
    vector<int> bestSel;
    for(int c = 0; c <= N; c++){
        if(dp[c].val <= NEG_INF/2) continue;
        double v = dp[c].val;
        int leftover = N - c;
        bool take = false;
        if(v > bestVal + EPS){
            take = true;
        } else if(fabs(v - bestVal) <= EPS){
            // more leftover => more leading 1's => lex-smaller
            if(leftover > (N - bestCost)) {
                take = true;
            } else if(leftover == (N - bestCost)){
                if(dp[c].sel < bestSel) take = true;
            }
        }
        if(take){
            bestVal = v;
            bestCost = c;
            bestSel = dp[c].sel;
        }
    }

    // 6) Output: first (N - bestCost) ones, then bestSel in ascending order
    bool first = true;
    for(int i = 0; i < N - bestCost; i++){
        if(!first) cout << ' ';
        cout << 1;
        first = false;
    }
    for(int x: bestSel){
        if(!first) cout << ' ';
        cout << x;
        first = false;
    }
    if(first){
        // N==0? not possible since N>=1. But guard anyway.
        cout << 1;
    }
    cout << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of key points:  
- We reduce the LCM‐maximization to picking disjoint prime‐powers under a sum constraint.  
- We do a multiple‐choice 0/1 knapsack, one group per prime.  
- We work in the log‐domain to turn products into sums, and we break ties in a way that later ensures maximal leftover (→ more leading 1’s → lex smaller) and finally lex‐min sequence of prime‐powers.

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We have 16 teams: `x` “weak” (always lose vs strong) and `16−x` “strong.”  
   - They play a 5-round Swiss‐system (BO1 in our simplification) where a team that reaches 3 wins “qualifies” (top-8), and a team that reaches 3 losses is eliminated.  
   - Within each round, teams are paired by identical (wins, losses) record, and we are free to choose pairings within each record‐group (no region constraints).  
   - Goal: maximize how many weak teams reach 3 wins before 3 losses.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - We simulate the Swiss rounds state‐by‐state.  A state is `(w,ℓ)` with `w<3,ℓ<3`.  
   - In each `(w,ℓ)` group we have `nW` weaks and `nS` strongs.  We pair:
     • weak–weak as much as possible (floor(nW/2) matches) ⇒ yields that many weak-wins (moves to `(w+1,ℓ)`) and same number of weak-losses (to `(w,ℓ+1)`).  
     • strong–strong as much as possible (floor(nS/2) matches), similarly.  
     • the leftover must be cross (weak vs strong), each gives 1 strong-win and 1 weak-loss.  
   - This greedy pairing maximizes weak wins and minimizes weak losses, and thus maximizes eventual weak qualifiers.  
   - We run up to 5 rounds, track how many weaks go into a “3-win” state, and sum them.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - We have at most 5 rounds and a constant number (≤9) of `(w,ℓ)` states per round.  
   - Each step does O(1) work → overall O(1) per test.  
   - Uses O(1) space beyond fixed arrays.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - `x=0` ⇒ no weak can qualify (answer 0).  
   - `x=16` ⇒ all weaks; they fully play a 16-player Swiss and exactly 8 qualify, so answer 8.  
   - Always ensure we drop teams that reach 3 losses or 3 wins.  

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Swiss Tournament Simulation (BO1 simplification)
   We greedily pair weak–weak and strong–strong first to maximize weak wins.
   Track states (wins, losses) for weak and strong teams separately.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int x;
    cin >> x;              // number of weak teams
    int sw[4][4] = {}, ss[4][4] = {};  // sw[w][l]: count of weak in state (w,l)
    sw[0][0] = x;
    ss[0][0] = 16 - x;

    int weak_qual = 0;

    // Run up to 5 rounds
    for(int round = 1; round <= 5; round++){
        int sw2[4][4] = {}, ss2[4][4] = {};

        // For each active state (w < 3, l < 3)
        for(int w = 0; w < 3; w++){
            for(int l = 0; l < 3; l++){
                int nW = sw[w][l], nS = ss[w][l];
                if(nW + nS == 0) continue;

                // Greedily pair weak-weak and strong-strong
                int m_WW = nW / 2;               // WW matches
                int m_SS = nS / 2;               // SS matches
                int totalMatches = (nW + nS) / 2;
                int m_SM = totalMatches - m_WW - m_SS;  // cross matches

                // 1) Weak wins come only from WW matches
                //    They move to (w+1, l)
                if(w + 1 == 3){
                    // They hit 3 wins ⇒ qualifiers
                    weak_qual += m_WW;
                } else {
                    sw2[w+1][l] += m_WW;
                }

                // 2) Weak losses come from WW losers and all cross matches
                int weak_losses = m_WW + m_SM;
                if(l + 1 < 3){
                    sw2[w][l+1] += weak_losses;
                }
                // otherwise they are eliminated (l+1 == 3)

                // 3) Strong wins = SS winners + all cross matches
                int strong_wins = m_SS + m_SM;
                if(w + 1 < 3){
                    ss2[w+1][l] += strong_wins;
                }
                // else strong qualifiers (we don't need to count them)

                // 4) Strong losses = SS losers
                if(l + 1 < 3){
                    ss2[w][l+1] += m_SS;
                }
                // else eliminated
            }
        }

        // Swap into current
        memcpy(sw, sw2, sizeof(sw));
        memcpy(ss, ss2, sizeof(ss));
    }

    // Output the maximum number of weak qualifiers
    cout << weak_qual << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of Key Steps:  
- We maintain `sw[w][l]` & `ss[w][l]` for counts of weak/strong in state `(wins=w, losses=l)` with `w<3, l<3`.  
- In each round, each state does its own pairing: maximize intra-type pairings to get as many weak wins as possible.  
- Moves: wins increment `w`, losses increment `l`.  
- Once a weak reaches `w=3` it’s counted as a qualifier. Losses at `l=3` are simply dropped.  
- After 5 rounds, we’ve accumulated all weak qualifiers.

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We have \(n\) pairs \((a_i,b_i)\). We must choose exactly \(s\) values from the \(a\)-side and \(t\) values from the \(b\)-side (with \(s+t\le n\)), never picking both from the same pair.  
   - Core categories: knapsack/assignment with two “colors” and cardinality constraints.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - A direct 2D DP on \((\#A,\#B)\) is \(O(n\,s\,t)\), too big for \(n\le5000\).  
   - We apply a *Lagrangian relaxation* on the count of \(A\)-selections.  Introduce a penalty \(\lambda\) for each picked \(a_i\).  For a guess \(\lambda\), define for each \(i\):  
        gain\_A = \(a_i + \lambda\),  gain\_B = \(b_i\).  
     We then pick the top \(k = s+t\) options among all \(2n\) (actually per item we take max of gain\_A, gain\_B)), and count how many came from \(A\).  As \(\lambda\) grows, more items favor \(A\).  We binary-search \(\lambda\) until exactly \(s\) of the top-\(k\) picks are from \(A\).  
   - Finally we correct the small offset from \(\lambda\) to recover the true maximum sum.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - For each \(\lambda\)-trial we do an \(O(n\log n)\) sort (or partial_sort) to pick the top \(k\).  
   - We binary-search \(\lambda\) over an integer range of about \([-5000,5000]\), i.e.\ \(O(\log 10^4)\approx 14\) steps.  
   - Total is \(O(n\log n\cdot \log C)\approx 5000\cdot12\cdot14\sim 10^6\), well within typical time limits.  
   - Space: \(O(n)\).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - \(s=0\) or \(t=0\) or \(s+t=0\).  Our scheme handles them uniformly (we’ll end up picking only \(b\)-values or none).  
   - Ties where \(a_i + \lambda = b_i\): we treat those as \(B\)-picks (consistent monotonicity).  
   - Make sure to subtract out the \(\lambda\)-bias after adjusting extra \(A\)-picks.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Lagrangian relaxation + binary search on penalty λ.
   For each λ, compute best_gain_i = max(b_i, a_i+λ), pick top k = s+t,
   count how many from A-side.  Binary-search λ so that count_A = s,
   then adjust minor over-count by dropping smallest diffs.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, s, t;
    cin >> n >> s >> t;
    vector<int> a(n), b(n);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> a[i];
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> b[i];
    int k = s + t;
    // Quick exit: pick only t best b[i] if s==0
    // or only s best a[i] if t==0 (but our general code handles s==0 or t==0).

    auto eval = [&](int lam){
        // Returns how many A-picks among top k with penalty lam
        static vector<pair<int,int>> V;
        V.clear();
        V.reserve(n);
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            int diff = (a[i] - b[i]) + lam;    // gainA - gainB
            int best_gain = b[i] + max(diff, 0);
            V.emplace_back(best_gain, diff);
        }
        nth_element(V.begin(), V.begin() + k, V.end(),
                    [](auto &L, auto &R){ return L.first > R.first; });
        int cntA = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < k; i++){
            if (V[i].second > 0) cntA++;
        }
        return cntA;
    };

    // Binary search smallest lam so that eval(lam) >= s
    int lo = -5000, hi = 5000;
    while(lo < hi){
        int mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
        if (eval(mid) >= s) hi = mid;
        else lo = mid + 1;
    }
    int lam = lo;

    // Final selection at lam, but also accumulate gains & diffs
    vector<pair<int,int>> V; // (best_gain, diff)
    V.reserve(n);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        int diff = (a[i] - b[i]) + lam;
        int best_gain = b[i] + max(diff, 0);
        V.emplace_back(best_gain, diff);
    }
    sort(V.begin(), V.end(),
         [](auto &L, auto &R){ return L.first > R.first; });

    // Sum the top k best_gain, collect diffs>0
    ll sum_gain = 0;
    vector<int> posDiff;
    posDiff.reserve(k);
    for(int i = 0; i < k; i++){
        sum_gain += V[i].first;
        if (V[i].second > 0)
            posDiff.push_back(V[i].second);
    }

    int cntA = (int)posDiff.size();
    int extra = cntA - s; // how many too many A-picks
    ll sum_remove = 0;
    if (extra > 0) {
        sort(posDiff.begin(), posDiff.end());
        for(int i = 0; i < extra; i++)
            sum_remove += posDiff[i];
    }

    // Remove the λ-bias from exactly s A-picks
    ll answer = sum_gain - sum_remove - ll(lam) * ll(s);
    cout << answer << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of key steps:
- We define for each item \(i\):  
    diff = \((a_i - b_i) + \lambda\).  
    best_gain = \(b_i + \max(\text{diff},0)\).  
  If diff>0, the item in the greedy pick would be taken on the \(A\)-side (counted) with gain \(a_i+\lambda\); otherwise on the \(B\)-side with gain \(b_i\).
- We pick the top \(k=s+t\) items by `best_gain` and count how many diff>0 (i.e.\ chosen as \(A\)).  By raising \(\lambda\), we increase that count.
- We binary-search the smallest \(\lambda\) for which the count ≥ \(s\).  That ensures we can meet the \(s\) quota, potentially with a slight over-pick.
- If we over-pick (\(\text{cntA} - s = \text{extra}>0\)), we “demote” the \(\text{extra}\) smallest diffs within those chosen items from \(A\) to \(B\), subtracting their diff from the total.
- Finally we subtract the accumulated \(\lambda\)-bias \(\lambda\cdot s\) to recover the true maximum sum of chosen \(s\) \(a_i\)s and \(t\) \(b_i\)s.

[Problem Analysis]

1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We need to split the integer N into positive summands whose total sum is exactly N, so that the LCM of those summands is maximized.  Since adding a “1” to the array does not change the LCM, the real question is how to choose a multiset of integers >1, summing to at most N, to maximize the LCM.  Observe that if the selected numbers are pairwise coprime then the LCM is simply their product.  However, if two chosen numbers share a prime factor, the LCM only accretes the higher exponent of that prime rather than multiplying both factors, so to maximize the LCM we should choose each prime factor at most once.

   - Thus, the problem reduces to a 0/1-knapsack on the available primes p ≤ N:  
     weight = p,  
     value = log(p)  (so that maximizing sum of logs ⇔ maximizing product of the primes)  
     capacity = N.  

   - After picking the optimal subset of primes whose weights sum to W ≤ N and whose log-sum is maximized, we pad with (N–W) ones to reach sum N.  Among equal-value knapsack solutions, we choose the one with the smallest W (so that we have the maximum number of leading ones, yielding lexicographically smallest output).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - Sieve all primes up to N in O(N log log N).  
   - Run a standard 0/1-knapsack DP over those primes:  
     dp[j] = maximum sum of logs achievable with total weight j.  
     prev[j], choice[j] to reconstruct which prime was used last.  
   - After filling dp[], scan j=0…N to pick the j with maximal dp[j], breaking ties by smaller j.  
   - Backtrack to find the chosen primes, sort them ascending.  Finally, output (N–j) ones followed by the chosen primes in ascending order.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Sieve: O(N log log N).  
   - Number of primes up to 5000 is ~669.  
   - Knapsack DP: O((#primes) * N) ≃ 669 * 5000 ≃ 3.3⋅10^6 operations.  
   - Space: O(N) for dp, prev, choice arrays.  
   This easily fits within typical contest limits.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - N = 1: no primes fit; answer is just [1].  
   - Floating-point precision when comparing sums of logs: use a small ε (e.g. 1e-12).  
   - Reconstructing the lexicographically smallest solution among ties: when dp is equal (within ε), prefer the smaller total weight j so as to pad with more leading ones.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Problem A: Maximize LCM by choosing summands summing to N.
   Key idea: pick a subset of primes (0/1-knapsack on weight=prime, value=log(prime))
   to maximize sum of logs ⇒ maximize product ⇒ maximize LCM.
   Pad with 1s to reach sum N; tie-break by fewer total prime‐sum (more leading 1s).
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N;
    cin >> N;

    // 1. Sieve primes up to N
    vector<bool> is_composite(N+1, false);
    vector<int> primes;
    for (int i = 2; i <= N; i++) {
        if (!is_composite[i]) {
            primes.push_back(i);
            if ((long long)i * i <= N) {
                for (int j = i*i; j <= N; j += i)
                    is_composite[j] = true;
            }
        }
    }

    // 2. Knapsack DP: dp[j] = max sum of logs for total weight j
    const double NEG_INF = -1e100;
    vector<double> dp(N+1, NEG_INF);
    vector<int> prev_idx(N+1, -1), choice(N+1, -1);
    dp[0] = 0.0;

    for (int i = 0; i < (int)primes.size(); i++) {
        int p = primes[i];
        double lp = log((double)p);
        // 0/1 knapsack: iterate backwards on weight
        for (int w = N; w >= p; w--) {
            double cand = dp[w-p] + lp;
            if (cand > dp[w] + 1e-12) {
                dp[w] = cand;
                prev_idx[w] = w - p;
                choice[w] = i;
            }
        }
    }

    // 3. Find best total prime-sum w ≤ N that maximizes dp[w], tie-breaking on smaller w
    double best_val = 0.0;
    int best_w = 0;
    for (int w = 1; w <= N; w++) {
        if (dp[w] > best_val + 1e-12 ||
           (fabs(dp[w] - best_val) < 1e-12 && w < best_w)) {
            best_val = dp[w];
            best_w = w;
        }
    }

    // 4. Reconstruct chosen primes
    vector<int> chosen;
    int cur = best_w;
    while (cur > 0 && choice[cur] != -1) {
        int idx = choice[cur];
        chosen.push_back(primes[idx]);
        cur = prev_idx[cur];
    }
    sort(chosen.begin(), chosen.end());

    // 5. Output: (N - best_w) ones, then the chosen primes
    int ones = N - best_w;
    bool first = true;
    for (int i = 0; i < ones; i++) {
        if (!first) cout << ' ';
        cout << 1;
        first = false;
    }
    for (int p: chosen) {
        if (!first) cout << ' ';
        cout << p;
        first = false;
    }
    // Special case: if N == 0 or N == 1, we should at least print one '1'
    if (N == 1) {
        if (!first) cout << ' ';
        cout << 1;
    }
    cout << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of key steps:
- We convert LCM-maximization into product-maximization under the constraint of pairwise coprimality; thus each prime may be chosen at most once.
- A 0/1 knapsack with value = log(prime) effectively maximizes the product of chosen primes.
- Padding with ones (which don’t affect LCM) ensures the sum is exactly N, and having more leading ones makes the output lexicographically smaller.
